# To print variable names (For axes names)

def namestr(obj, namespace):
    return [name for name in namespace if namespace[name] is obj]

Looking at the plots, I can say that the some of the specific features have low values for Class 1 (Green Line), lower than the Class 0 counterpart of the same feature. Therefore, applying min transformation to the bag features might be useful and representative of the bag (for classifaction purpose). Also, with this representation, the aim is to define if some features are below a certain level or not, in order to classify the bag. Since values of some specific features are our concern, a tree-based algorithm would be a good fit for this scenario, giving these features very high importances. Also, I will try SVM Classifier, because it is stated as 'State of the Art Classifier' during the lecture.¶

2. HAUSDORFF DISTANCE¶

In [22]:
# https://arxiv.org/pdf/1309.5643.pdf

# In this paper, bag dissimarity representation methods are proposed for the MIL problems, and seems to give good results.
# Therefore, I will be trying one of the proposed dissimilarity approaches, namely 'Hausdorff Distance'.It makes sense that
# bags that are closer in terms of this distance will be more likely to belong to same class. The distance is defined as
# such: "Hausdorff Distance between two point sets is the largest of the distances between each possible pair (a,b), such 
# that 'a' belongs to the first set and 'b' belongs to the second set.".

# Pick the first bag from the dataset, that has class=1
a = new_df[new_df["Bag Id"]==1].iloc[:,2:].copy()

# Select the bags that belong to class1, and bags that belong to class 2.

class1_dict = {}
class2_dict = {}

for i in range(1,48):
    class1_dict[i] = new_df[new_df["Bag Id"]==i].iloc[:,2:].to_numpy()
    
for i in range(48,93):
    class2_dict[i] = new_df[new_df["Bag Id"]==i].iloc[:,2:].to_numpy()
In [25]:
# Calculate the Hausdorff distances from the bag with id=1, to the other bags.

class1_len = []
for i in class1_dict.values():
    class1_len.append(directed_hausdorff(i, a)[0])
    
class2_len = []
for i in class2_dict.values():
    class2_len.append(directed_hausdorff(i, a)[0])

# It seems like bags that have the same class, in average, has a lower hausdorff distance to the bag1 . Therefore, they are
# more similar, (less dissimilar) to the bag1.

Let's convert all the points to the Hausdorff distance.¶

In [29]:
# Merge class1 and class2 point sets
z = {**class1_dict, **class2_dict}
In [30]:
# Create the new feature matrix, a distance-matrix, by creating distance vectors for each bag (using Hausdorff distance of
# that bag to the other bags).

new_distances = {}
for i in range(1,93):
    distances = []
    for j in range(1,93):
        distances.append(directed_hausdorff(new_df[new_df["Bag Id"]==i].iloc[:,2:],
                                            new_df[new_df["Bag Id"]==j].iloc[:,2:])[0])
    new_distances[f"bag{i}"] = distances
In [31]:
# Specify the Input and Target features

new_features = pd.DataFrame(new_distances).T
classes = df.groupby("Bag Id")["Bag class"].mean()
